    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Montour Falls gets its name from a waterfall at the end of West Main Street.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montour_Falls%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The village sits on the former Seneca village Queanettquaga, known as Catherine's Town after Queen Catharine Montour.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        21,
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montour_Falls%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The village’s historic heart features Chequaga Falls, one of seven natural glens and more than 20 waterfalls in the area.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://pocketsights.com/tours/place/Montour-Falls-NY-80869:8445"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The New York State Academy of Fire Science, a state‑run institution, is located in Montour Falls.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montour_Falls%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Charles Cook, a canal commissioner and philanthropist, founded the Cook Academy in 1858, which later became the Academy of Fire Science.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Montour_Falls%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Montour Falls is the southern gateway to the Finger Lakes Region, noted for its natural and historical beauty.",
